reviewText: A more comprehensive review of the movie (by yours truly) can be found on IMDB movie database. Suffice to say that 'THE BIRDS AND THE BEES' has more of everything (color, music, chemistry, plausibility, set direction, cast, comedy, et cetera)  than the original THE LADY EVE. A curious note: I have the VHS and the movie looks better than the AMAZON instant video. I wait patiently for a very credible DVD  release! I think Mitzi and George are way better than Stanwyck and Fonda.
summary: The Lady Who?? has more of everything

reviewText: For fans of Preston Sturges' 'The Lady Eve' (1941) this unnecessary but nearly-as-amusing 1956 remake provides an interesting look at the sharp-witted screwball original (4-plus stars) through the decidedly less sophisticated Technicolor lens of a 1950s romantic musical-comedy. In fact, though one can hardly compare the screen presence of leading man George Gobel with that of Henry Fonda (ditto for Ms. Gaynor and Ms. Stanwyck in their respective roles, with David Niven a fine proxy for the great Charles Coburn), the replacement cast delivers laughs on a par-- in quantity if not always quality-- with their iconic counterparts. For those not familiar with TLE, 'The Birds and the Bees' remains a light and enjoyable 90 minutes filled with good performances, which I hope will be sufficient inspiration for them to check out its classic predecessor. 3-plus stars.

reviewText: While this movie could never have won an academy award, is clearly dated in many ways, its plot and script were interesting enough for us to watch the movie all the way through. The movie was obviously produced as a vehicle for George Gobel to star in a movie with some box-office names, but his performance wasn't bad. On the other hand, Mitzi Gaynor's performance was very good for the material she was given.
